<article>
    <h1>When bread doesn&#x2019;t sell like hot&#xAD;cakes</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201211/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-11"><time>2020-12-11</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Every day, close to the end of the busi­ness day at 10pm, vol­un­teers from lo­cal food char­ity Food From The Heart march to more than 100 bak­eries across the is­land to pick up bags of un­sold bread and de­liver them to wel­fare homes, halfway houses and many oth­ers in need in the vicin­ity.</p>
    <p>About 28,000kg of bread des­tined for the bins are sal­vaged in this man­ner every month. Last year, the non-profit res­cued 336,000kg of bread worth more than $3.5 mil­lion. The Sun­day Times looks at how or­gan­i­sa­tions here are work­ing with busi­nesses to save sur­plus food from the bin.</p>

